Touch Command:
This is generally used for creating the files. But, this can also be used for setting the access, time the file is created.
Update only access time (atime): touch -a filename.txt
Update only modification time (mtime): touch -m filename.txt
Set a specific date and time, The format is [[CC]YY]MMDDhhmm[.ss]: touch -t 202605311230.30 filename.txt
Use a reference file: Updates filename.txt to match the timestamps of reference.txt : touch -r reference.txt filename.txt
Don't create the file if it's missing: Only updates the timestamp if the file already exists : touch -c filename.txt

cd - ==> This command is used for change to the last visited path
cd . ==> Changes your directory to the exact folder you are already in, which essentially does nothing and acts as a safe "refresh."
cd .. ==> change to the directory above your current i.e parent directory
cd    ==> change to your home directory
cd ~ ===> change to your home directory
cd / ===> change to the root directory

The -r (or -R in some commands) flag allows the user to run a certain command recursively. For example, listing all the files under the following tree is possible when done recursively (ls -R)
To list all the files, one can run ls -R /dir1

